{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2013}} {{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> | name = Edwin Philip Pister | image = Phil Pister.jpeg | imagesize = | caption = | pseudonym = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date|1929|1|15}} | birth_place = [[Stockton, California]] | death_date = | death_place = | occupation = Fishery Biologist, Conservationist, Deep Ecologist | nationality = American | period = | genre = | subject = Desert fishes, conservation, environmental ethics | movement = | notableworks = | alma mater = | spouse = | partner = | children = | relatives = | influences = | influenced = | awards = | signature = | website = }} '''Edwin "Phil" Pister''' is a fishery biologist who worked for California Department of Fish and Game.<ref>{{cite news|last1=ROBERTS|first1=RICH|title=Fish Came First : Phil Pister Didn't Make a Lot of Friends, but He Made a Mark in 37 Years at DFG|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-08-01/sports/sp-1430_1_phil-pister-didn-t-make|work=Los Angeles Times|date=1 August 1990}}</ref> He was a pioneer of desert fish conservation, and is credited with saving the [[Owens pupfish]] (''Cyprinodon radiosis'') by transferring the entire remaining population into several buckets and transporting them to a safe location.<ref name=pister2>Pister, E. P. [http://www.montana.edu/~wwwbi/staff/mcmahon/Pister.pdf Species in a bucket.] ''Natural History Magazine'' (January 1993). pg 14. Retrieved September 29, 2011.</ref><ref name=albert>Terrill, C. "Islands". In: Albert, S. W. [https://books.google.com/books?id=Zojc-U3EkIIC&pg=PA129&lpg=PA129&dq=Owen+pupfish+buckets&source=bl&ots=uW-rso6a5l&sig=Nv4o49cCLWnjqb6zCcNb9G02lLU&hl=en&ei=zfKDTp7OBoKosAK3meSNDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q&f=false What Wildness is This: Women Write About the Southwest.] University of Texas Press. (2007). pg 129. Retrieved September 29, 2011.</ref>
Pister was born in [[Stockton, California]] and currently lives in [[Bishop, California]]. A volume compiling studies of desert fishes has been published in his honor.<ref>{{cite book |editors=Ma. De Lourdes Lozano-Vilano and Armando J. Contreras-Balderas |title=Studies of North American Desert Fishes in Honor of E.P.(Phil) Pister Conservationist |chapter=Conservation of Mexican Native Trout and The Discovery, Status, Protection and Recovery Of The Conchos Trout, The First Native |authors=Dean A. Hendrickson, David A. Neely, Richard L. Mayden, Karl Anderson, James E. Brooks, Faustino Camarena-Rosales, Ralph Clitter, Lisa Cutter, Anna Bellia De Los Santos, Guy W. Ernsting, Hector Espinosa-Perez, Lloyd T. Findley, Francisco J. Garcia-De León, Anna L. George, John Hatch, Bernard R. Kuhajda, Kyle E. Mayden, Kristina Mcnyset, Jennifer L. Nielseni, Frank W. Pfeifer, David L. Propst, Gorgonio Ruiz-Campos, Eric St. Clair, Joseph R. Tomelleri and Alejandro Varela-Romero |date=November 2006 |publisher=Universidad Autónoma de Nuevo Leon |location=Monterrey, Mexico |isbn=970-694-336-6 }}</ref> He has written and published scientific and popular papers and has also written about environmental ethics.<ref>{{cite journal |last = Pister |first = E. Phil |title = The Rights of Species and Ecosystems |journal = Fisheries |year = 1995 |volume = 20 |issue = 4 |url = http://www.nativefish.org/articles/Fish_Rights.php |accessdate = 2006-04-25 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060822184859/http://www.nativefish.org/articles/Fish_Rights.php |archivedate = August 22, 2006 |df = mdy-all }}</ref>
He has served as executive secretary of the [[Desert Fishes Council]].<ref name=USFWS>.{{cite web|last1=Springer|first1=Craig|title=Pioneers: Edwin "Phil" Pister|url=http://www.fws.gov/eddies/episodeFall_Winter2013/pioneers/index.html|website=Fish and Aquatic Conservation|publisher=US Fish and Wildlife Service|accessdate=9 May 2015}}</ref>
==Awards== * Order of the Jassid (for conservation) from Sierra Pacific Flyfishers * President’s Fishery Conservation Award from the American Fisheries Society * The Edward T. LaRoe III Memorial Award from the [[Society for Conservation Biology]]. * 2018 [[Andrea Mead Lawrence|Andrea Lawrence]] Award from the [[Mono Lake Committee]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Andrea Lawrence Award Dinner|url=http://www.monolake.org/mlc/alad|accessdate=5 May 2018|work=www.monolake.org}}</ref>
